org.parboiled.parserunners

Class TracingParseRunner<V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.parboiled.parserunners.AbstractParseRunner<V>
      • org.parboiled.parserunners.ReportingParseRunner<V>
        • org.parboiled.parserunners.TracingParseRunner<V>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    MatchHandler, ParseRunner<V>

    public class TracingParseRunner<V>
extends ReportingParseRunner<V>
implements MatchHandler
    A ParseRunner implementation used for debugging purposes. It exhibits the same behavior as the ReportingParseRunner but collects debugging information as to which rules did match and which didn't.

      • getLog

        @Deprecated
 @DoNotUse
 @Unused
 @WillBeRemoved(version="1.1")
public Sink<String> getLog()
        Deprecated. 
        Deprecated, and does nothing! Read description...

        Unfortunately, the original documentation about parser debugging would have you believe that this method was important to obtain the debug output.

        But that is not the case. What happens in reality is that the output shown in the documentation is the result of the parsing run itself, since by default it uses a SystemOutCharSink (before that, it was the now deprecated ConsoleSink). The only exception to that is if you used a StringBuilderSink to the withLog(Sink) method (now also deprecated), because this sink implementation does overwrite .toString() -- which the Sink implementation does not require, therefore do not rely on it.

        Returns:
        a sink, which may, or may not, implement Object.toString().
